heir letters offers a profound insight into their subjectivity and agency over time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aDiachronic. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedia Studies. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEpistolarity, Gender, Family, Women.1 aGarrioch, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJames, Carolyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048556427zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048556427/original  a978-3-11-102374-8 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA